\begin_layout Section
Investments and Capital Stocks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
First attempt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=\tau K_{t}^{\kappa}L_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Labor productivity is given as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MPL=\frac{\partial y}{\partial L}=\tau K_{t}^{\kappa}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that each firm faces a demand function with constant elasticity,
 the domestic price level will be given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=(1+\mu)\frac{W}{MPL}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the nominal wage level.
 We assume that firms' profits will be paid out to capital holders.
 The firms' nominal profits are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Pi & = & Py-WL=(1+\mu)\frac{W}{MPL}\cdot MPL\cdot L-WL\\
 & = & (1+\mu)\frac{W}{MPL}\cdot MPL\cdot L-W\cdot L\\
 & = & \mu\cdot W\cdot L
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The firm's real profits are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Pi}{P}=\frac{\mu}{1+\mu}\frac{L}{MPL}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we assume that these profits are paid out to capital owners, we have
 the following real profit per capital owner:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
r_{K} & = & \frac{\Pi/P}{K}=\frac{\mu}{1+\mu}\frac{L}{K\cdot MPL}\\
 & = & \frac{\mu}{1+\mu}\frac{L}{K\cdot\tau K^{\kappa}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is a weird prediction: A larger productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 leads to lower real returns to capital...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\frac{1}{1-\eta}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mu}{1+\mu}=\frac{\frac{1}{1-\eta}}{1+\frac{1}{1-\eta}}=\frac{1}{1-\eta+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
