\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=\tau K_{t}^{\kappa}L_{t}^{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Labor and capital productivity are given as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
MPL & = & \frac{\partial y}{\partial L}=\lambda\tau K^{\kappa}L^{\lambda-1}=\frac{\lambda y}{L}\\
MPK & = & \frac{\partial y}{\partial K}=\kappa\tau K^{\kappa-1}L^{\lambda}=\frac{\kappa y}{K}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marginal cost of labor is given as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MC_{L}=\frac{W}{MPL}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marginal cost of capital: a firm rents one unit of capital for one period
 at a nominal interest rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The capital depreciates, but the firm has to give back the whole unit of
 capital.
 So marginal cost to produce one extra output unit with the unit of capital
 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MC_{K}=\frac{i+\delta P}{MPK}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In equilibrium with market power, firm's choose labor, capital and prices
 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=(1+\mu)(MC_{L})=(1+\mu)(MC_{K})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firms' nominal revenues are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Py & = & (1+\mu)\frac{W}{MPL}\cdot\frac{L}{\lambda}MPL\\
 & = & \frac{(1+\mu)}{\lambda}WL
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firms' nominal profits are given
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Pi & = & Py-WL-iK\\
 & = & \left(\frac{(1+\mu)}{\lambda}-1\right)WL-iK
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
